Semantic Similarity using FastText

Semantic similarity is a similarity between two words how close their meanings are for the given context (using n-grams) and it is a number between 0 to 1 which tells us how close two words are, semantically. This is done by finding similarity between word vectors in the vector space, (ie) what is the probaility of a context word appearing next to a target word based on corpus of text on which the model has been trained on. we will see how FastText library creates vector representations that can be used to find semantic similarities between the words using skip grams or CBOW.

we will implement the skip-gram model to learn vector representation of words from the Wikipedia articles on artificial intelligence, machine learning, deep learning, neural networks, Marvel, DC Comics and Bible. Since these topics are quite different, we can have a substantial amount of data to create a corpus and also to create a semantic similarity between the words of the given context. You can add more topics of the similar nature if you want.

As a first step, we need to import the required libraries. We will make use of the Wikipedia library for Python, which can be downloaded via the following command:

$ pip install wikipedia

we are using the FastText module from the gensim.models.fasttext library. For the word representation and semantic similarity, we can use the Gensim model for FastText. This model can run on Windows, however, for text classification, we will have to use Linux platform.

Scraping Wikipedia Articles¶

To scrape a Wikipedia page, we can use the page method from the wikipedia module. The name of the page that you want to scrap is passed as a parameter to the page method. The method returns WikipediaPage object, which you can then use to retrieve the page contents via the content attribute, as shown in the below script.

In [4]:
artificial_intelligence = wikipedia.page("Artificial Intelligence").content
bible = wikipedia.page("bible book").content 
deep_learning = wikipedia.page("Deep Learning").content
neural_network = wikipedia.page("Neural Network").content
marvel = wikipedia.page("marvel books").content
dc = wikipedia.page("dc superheroes").content

Now we will combine all the text into a big corpus by using extend method, then we need to convert into corpus of sentences (but not corpus of words , because often the relationship between words will be obtained only in the same sentence which provides its context). Hence if we change the whole text into corpus of words then those meaning will be lost as there is no sentence to learn the context in whcih it has to appear, thus the sentences are important when it comes to semantic similarity.

In [7]:
artificial_intelligence= list(nlp(artificial_intelligence).sents) #to break the given text into sentences first using Spacy
bible= list(nlp(bible).sents)

neural_network= list(nlp(neural_network).sents)
marvel= list(nlp(marvel).sents)
dc= list(nlp(dc).sents)

artificial_intelligence.extend(neural_network)
artificial_intelligence.extend(marvel)
artificial_intelligence.extend(dc)

Text Pre-processing¶

After successfully scraping off the content from the coressponding web pages of wikipedia and combines them, we will clean the text data by removing the punctuations and stop words then we have to do Lemmatization to stem the words. We will be using spacy for this Pre-processing whcih is excellent at the Lemmatization process.

In [30]:
def spacy_tokenizer(word):
    a = nlp(word) #tokenization
    b=[]
    for token in a:
        if (token.is_stop != True) and (token.is_punct != True) and (token.is_alpha == True):#Stop words and punc removal
            b.append(token.lemma_) #Lemmatization
    return b
In [31]:
final_corpus = [spacy_tokenizer(str(sent)) for sent in corpus]

FastText Model
In [37]:
embedding_size = 60
window_size = 30
min_word = 5
down_sampling = 1e-2

ft_model = FastText(final_corpus,size=embedding_size,window=window_size,min_count=min_word,sample=down_sampling,sg=1,iter=100)

Here embedding_size is the size of the embedding vector. In other words, each word in our corpus will be represented as a 60-dimensional vector.

The window_size is the size of the number of words occurring before and after the word based on which the word representations will be learned for the word. This might sound tricky, however in the skip-gram model we input a word to the algorithm and the output is the context words. If the window size is 40, for each input there will be 80 outputs: 40 words that occur before the input word and 40 words that occur after the input word. The word embeddings for the input word are learned using these 80 output words.

The next hyper-parameter is the min_word, which specifies the minimum frequency of a word in the corpus for which the word representations will be generated.

All the parameters in the above script are self-explanatory, except sg. The sg parameter defines the type of model that we want to create. A value of 1 specifies that we want to create skip-gram model. Whereas zero specifies the bag of words model, which is the default value as well

Finally, the most frequently occurring word will be down-sampled by a number specified by the down_sampling attribute.

Let's now see the word representation for the word "artificial". To do so, you can use the wv method of the FastText object and pass it the name of the word inside a list.

we can also find the similarity between two words by using the wv.most_similar method of the ft_model and extract the top n similar words which are closer semantically

In [59]:
semantically_similar_words = {words: [item[0] for item in ft_model.wv.most_similar([words], topn=8)]
                  for words in ['artificial', 'god', 'network', 'jesus','satan','heroes','superman', 'steve rogers']}

for k,v in semantically_similar_words.items():
    print(k+":"+str(v)+'\n')

Visualizing Word Similarities¶

Though each word in our model is represented as 60-dimensional vector, we can use principal component analysis technique to find two principal components. The two principal components can then be used to plot the words in a two dimensional space. However, first we need to create a list of all the words in the semantically_similar_words dictionary. The following script does that:

In [74]:
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA

all_similar_words = sum([[k] + v for k, v in semantically_similar_words.items()], [])

print(all_similar_words)
print(type(all_similar_words))
print(len(all_similar_words))

['artificial', 'intelligence', 'biological', 'neural', 'machine', 'Intelligence', 'Artificial', 'behavior', 'network', 'god', 'good', 'authority', 'Christianity', 'Holy', 'God', 'humanity', 'actually', 'difficulty', 'network', 'neural', 'neuron', 'biological', 'processing', 'model', 'deep', 'learning', 'approximation', 'jesus', 'Jesus', 'holy', 'Jeremiah', 'Wisdom', 'Timothy', 'Letter', 'Baruch', 'Prayer', 'satan', 'Stan', 'Lee', 'artist', 'Jim', 'amazing', 'Kirby', 'Doctor', 'guardian', 'heroes', 'Superheroes', 'DC', 'Heroes', 'Mattel', 'figure', 'Superman', 'Super', 'Batman', 'superman', 'Superman', 'League', 'Justice', 'superhero', 'Black', 'Batman', 'America', 'Doctor', 'steve rogers', 'Avengers', 'guardian', 'collectible', 'Galaxy', 'Doctor', 'Daredevil', 'Iron', 'Hulk']
<class 'list'>
72

Next, we have to find the word vectors for all these 30 words, and then use PCA to reduce the dimensions of the word vectors from 60 to 2. We can then use the plt method, which is an alias of the matplotlib.pyplot method to plot the words on a two-dimensional vector space.

In [88]:
word_vectors = ft_model.wv[all_similar_words]

pca = PCA(n_components=2)

p_comps = pca.fit_transform(word_vectors)
word_names = all_similar_words

plt.figure(figsize=(18, 10))
plt.scatter(p_comps[:, 0], p_comps[:, 1], c='red')

for word_names, x, y in zip(word_names, p_comps[:, 0], p_comps[:, 1]):
    plt.annotate(word_names, xy=(x+0.06, y+0.03), xytext=(0, 0), textcoords='offset points')

You can see the words that frequently occur together in the text are close to each other in the two dimensional plane as well. For instance, the words "deep" and "network" are almost overlapping. Similarly, the words "deep" and "intelligence" are also very close.
